The '''Cuban black hawk''' ('''''Buteogallus gundlachii''''') is a [[bird of prey]] in the [[Family (taxonomy)|family]] [[Accipitridae]]. It is [[endemic]] to [[Cuba]] and several outlying [[cay]]s.

==Taxonomy==
German ornithologist [[Jean Cabanis]] described the Cuban black hawk in 1855. It was considered by most authorities to be a subspecies of the [[Mangrove black hawk|Mangrove Black Hawk]] (''Buteogallus anthracinus''), although aspects of its behavior were little studied. However, in 2007, the [[American Ornithologists' Union]] classified it as a separate species based on differing vocalizations and plumage patterns.<ref name=Wiley2005/>

It is one of eight species in the New World genus ''[[Buteogallus]]''.

== Description ==
The species has an average body length of {{convert|53|cm|in|abbr=on}}. The plumage is mainly dark brown verging on black. A lighter greyish or whitish patch may be present on the face between the bill and the eye. White patches at the base of the primary flight feathers are visible in flight. The tail is striped with wide black and white bands. The legs are yellow and the bill is yellow tipped in black. Generally, females tend to be slightly larger in size than males.<ref name=BofCuba/>
